\hypertarget{part1-regressing-problems}{%
\section{PART1 : Regressing Problems}\label{part1-regressing-problems}}

\hypertarget{problem-1-insurance-company}{%
\subsection{Problem 1: Insurance
Company}\label{problem-1-insurance-company}}

The numbers of insured persons y with an insurance company for the years
1987 to 1996 are given. We let x represent the number of years since
1987 (x = 0 for 1987, x = 9 for 1996).

\hypertarget{dataset}{%
\subsubsection{1.1 Dataset}\label{dataset}}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3205}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.2671}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.4124}}@{}}
\toprule()
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{x (years since 1987)}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{Year}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{y (insured persons)}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule()
\endhead
0 & 1987 & 12,400 \\
1 & 198\RL{8} & 10,900 \\
2 & 198\RL{9} & 10,000 \\
\textbf{3} & 19\RL{90} & \textbf{1,050 (OUTLIER)} \\
4 & 19\RL{91} & 9,500 \\
5 & 19\RL{92} & 8,900 \\
6 & 19\RL{93} & 8,000 \\
7 & 19\RL{94} & 7,800 \\
8 & 19\RL{95} & 7,600 \\
9 & 19\RL{96} & 7,200 \\
\bottomrule()
\end{longtable}

\emph{* Value 1050 at x = 3 (year 1990) is the outlier --- likely a data
entry error or anomaly.}

\hypertarget{case-a-with-outlier}{%
\subsubsection{1.2 Case A: WITH Outlier}\label{case-a-with-outlier}}

\hypertarget{scatter-plot-outlier-identification}{%
\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{1. Scatter Plot \& Outlier
Identification}}{1. Scatter Plot \& Outlier Identification}}\label{scatter-plot-outlier-identification}}

A scatter plot of y (number of insured persons) versus x (years since
1987) reveals a generally decreasing trend from \textasciitilde12,400
down to \textasciitilde7,200. However, one data point stands out
sharply:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  x = 3 (year 1990): y = 1050
\end{itemize}

This value is dramatically lower than the surrounding data , which are
all within the range of approximately \textbf{7,200 to 12,400}. The
sharp drop at this point breaks the otherwise smooth downward trend.

Therefore, this observation is identified as a clear outlier, most
likely due to a data entry error (for example, a missing digit such as
\emph{10,500} instead of \emph{1,050}).

\includegraphics[width=6.34375in,height=4.84375in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image3.png}

\protect\hypertarget{_Toc226462961}{}{}Figure : Scatter plot of original
dataset identifying the outlier at x = 3 (y = 1050)

\hypertarget{regression-models-with-outlier}{%
\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2. Regression Models (WITH
Outlier)}}{2. Regression Models (WITH Outlier)}}\label{regression-models-with-outlier}}

We apply both OLS and matrix-form methods to compute linear model
parameters, then use the matrix form for quadratic and cubic models.

\hypertarget{linear-model}{%
\subparagraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{\emph{2.}1 Linear
Model}}{2.1 Linear Model}}\label{linear-model}}

\begin{itemize}
\item ~
  \hypertarget{hand-analysis-ols-method}{%
  \subparagraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{Hand Analysis (OLS
  Method)}}{Hand Analysis (OLS Method)}}\label{hand-analysis-ols-method}}
\end{itemize}

The equation for the linear model is given as follows:

\[\widehat{y_{i}} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}x_{i}\]

The key formulas used are:

\(\widehat{\beta_{1}} = \frac{\sum_{i = i}^{n}{x_{i}y_{i}}\ \  - \ \ \frac{\left( \sum_{i = 1}^{n}x_{i} \right)\left( \sum_{i = 1}^{n}y_{i} \right)}{n}}{\sum_{i = 1}^{n}x_{i}^{2\ \ } - \ \ \ \frac{\left( \sum_{i = 1}^{n}x_{i} \right)^{2}}{n}}\)
, \(\widehat{\beta_{0}} = \widehat{y}\  - \ \widehat{\beta_{i}}x\)

Data Table for Hand Computation\RL{:}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 10\tabcolsep) * \real{0.1098}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 10\tabcolsep) * \real{0.1122}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 10\tabcolsep) * \real{0.1572}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 10\tabcolsep) * \real{0.1572}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 10\tabcolsep) * \real{0.1974}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 10\tabcolsep) * \real{0.2663}}@{}}
\toprule()
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{year}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{xᵢ}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{yᵢ}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{xᵢ²}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{yᵢ²}
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\textbf{xᵢyᵢ}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule()
\endhead
1987 & 0 & 12400 & 0 & 153,760,000 & 0 \\
1988 & 1 & 10900 & 1 & 118,810,000 & 10,900 \\
1989 & 2 & 10000 & 4 & 100,000,000 & 20,000 \\
1990 & 3 & 1050 & 9 & 1,102,500 & 3,150 \\
1991 & 4 & 9500 & 16 & 90,250,000 & 38,000 \\
