\hypertarget{case-a-with-outlier-1}{%
\subsubsection{2.2 Case A: WITH Outlier}\label{case-a-with-outlier-1}}

\hypertarget{scatter-plot-outlier-identification-1}{%
\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{1. Scatter Plot \& Outlier
Identification}}{1. Scatter Plot \& Outlier Identification}}\label{scatter-plot-outlier-identification-1}}

A 3D scatter plot of Oil Usage vs. Temperature and Insulation reveals
that one data point is far outside the cluster formed by the other
observations: the point (Temp=65°F, Insulation=40 in, Oil=233 gallons).
All other insulation values range from 4 to 10 inches; an insulation
thickness of 40 inches is physically unreasonable for a typical
single-family home and is almost certainly a data entry error (e.g., the
value 4 recorded as 40). This point is identified as the outlier and is
highlighted in red in the scatter plot below.

\includegraphics[width=6.20833in,height=4.36863in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image25.png}

\protect\hypertarget{_Toc226462982}{}{}Figure : 3D Scatter Plot to
Detect Outlier (outlier in red: Insulation=40)

\hypertarget{regression-models}{%
\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2. Regression
Models}}{2. Regression Models}}\label{regression-models}}

\hypertarget{linear-model-2}{%
\subparagraph[\textbf{2.1 Linear
Model}]{\texorpdfstring{\protect\includegraphics[width=6.96944in,height=3.80833in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image26.png}\textbf{2.1
Linear Model}}{2.1 Linear Model}}\label{linear-model-2}}

The multivariate linear model has the form:

\[Oil = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}*\ T\  + \beta_{2}*\ I\ \]

where T = Temp, I = Insulation

\[Oil = 426.97\  - \ 5.274*T\  + 1.966*I\ \]

\includegraphics[width=7in,height=1.23611in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image27.png}

\protect\hypertarget{_Toc226462984}{}{}Figure : Simulation Results of
Linear Regression Surface (With Outlier)

So, the linear fit equation for the original dataset is:

\[\widehat{y_{i}} = 426.97 - \ 5.27x_{1i} + 1.966\ \ x_{2i}\]

The Coefficient of Determination (R²):

R² (Linear, With Outlier) = 0.6967

\hypertarget{quadratic-model-2}{%
\subparagraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2.2 Quadratic
Model}}{2.2 Quadratic Model}}\label{quadratic-model-2}}

\includegraphics[width=7.02361in,height=3.86806in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image28.png}

\protect\hypertarget{_Toc226462985}{}{}Figure : 3D Quadratic Regression
Surface (With Outlier), R² = 0.9742

The multivariate linear model has the form:

\[Oil = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}\ T\  + \beta_{2}\ I\  + \beta_{3}T^{2} + \beta_{4}TI + \beta_{5}{\ I}^{2}\]

\includegraphics[width=7in,height=1.62639in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image29.png}where
T = Temp, I = Insulation

\[Oil = 680.03\  - \ 6.168\ T\  - \ 41.716\ I\  - \ 0.01248\ T^{2} + 0.2392\ TI + 0.6586{\ I}^{2}\]

So, the quadratic fit equation for the original dataset is:

\[\widehat{y_{i}} = 680\  - \ 6.17x_{1i} - 41.72\ x_{2i} - \ 0.012\ x_{1i}^{2} + 0.24\ x_{1i}x_{2i} + 0.66\ x_{2i}^{2}\]

The Coefficient of Determination (R²):

R² (Quadratic, With Outlier) = 0.9742

\hypertarget{case-b-without-outlier-1}{%
\subsubsection{2.3 Case B: WITHOUT
Outlier}\label{case-b-without-outlier-1}}

\hypertarget{scatter-plot-outlier-identification-without-outlier}{%
\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{1. Scatter Plot \& Outlier
Identification (WITHOUT
Outlier)}}{1. Scatter Plot \& Outlier Identification (WITHOUT Outlier)}}\label{scatter-plot-outlier-identification-without-outlier}}

The data point (Temp=65, Insulation=40, Oil=233) is removed. All
remaining 14 data points have insulation values between 4 and 10 inches,
which is physically reasonable. The cleaned scatter plot is shown below.

\includegraphics[width=5.9375in,height=3.86111in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image30.png}

\hypertarget{regression-models-without-outlier-1}{%
\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2. Regression Models (WITHOUT
Outlier)}}{2. Regression Models (WITHOUT Outlier)}}\label{regression-models-without-outlier-1}}

\hypertarget{linear-model-3}{%
\subparagraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2.1 Linear
Model}}{2.1 Linear Model}}\label{linear-model-3}}

\includegraphics[width=6.74797in,height=3.93092in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image31.png}

\protect\hypertarget{_Toc226462988}{}{}Figure : 3D Linear Regression
Surface (Cleaned Data), R² = 0.9606

The multivariate linear model has the form:

\[Oil = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}*\ T\  + \beta_{2}*\ I\ \]

where T = Temp, I = Insulation

\[Oil = 601.6\  - \ 5.482\ T\  - \ 23.232\ I\ \]

\includegraphics[width=7in,height=1.23333in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image32.png}

\protect\hypertarget{_Toc226462989}{}{}Figure : Simulation Results of
Linear Regression Surface (Cleaned Data)

So, the linear fit equation for the original dataset is:

\[\widehat{y_{i}} = 601.6 - \ 5.482\ x_{1i} + 23.232\ \ x_{2i}\]

The Coefficient of Determination (R²):

R² (Linear, With Outlier) = 0.96061

\hypertarget{quadratic-model-3}{%
\subparagraph{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2.2 Quadratic
Model}}{2.2 Quadratic Model}}\label{quadratic-model-3}}

\includegraphics[width=6.70226in,height=3.7597in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image33.png}

\protect\hypertarget{_Toc226462990}{}{}Figure : 3D Quadratic Regression
Surface (Cleaned Data), R² = 0.9769

The multivariate quadratic model has the form:

\[Oil = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}\ T\  + \beta_{2}\ I\  + \beta_{3}T^{2} + \beta_{4}TI + \beta_{5}{\ I}^{2}\]

where T = Temp, I = Insulation

\[Oil = 785.52 - \ 6.963\ T\  - \ 72.159\ I\  - \ 0.00348\ T^{2} + 0.2567\ TI + 2.7438{\ I}^{2}\]

\includegraphics[width=7in,height=1.62917in]{vertopal_949f0de44c59406998abca066c65aa34/media/image34.png}

\protect\hypertarget{_Toc226462991}{}{}Figure : Simulation Results of
Quadratic Regression Surface (Cleaned Data)

So, the linear fit equation for the original dataset is:

\[\widehat{y_{i}} = 785.52\  - \ 6.963\ x_{1i} - 72.159\ x_{2i} - \ 0.00348\ x_{1i}^{2} + 0.2567\ x_{1i}x_{2i} + 2.7438\ x_{2i}^{2}\]

The Coefficient of Determination (R²):

R² (Quadratic, With Outlier) = 0.9769

